ople|ja|漢民族|12=draft}} settled there, importing Han {{ill|culture|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|12=draft}}; recent investigations have uncovered various relics in and around Pyongyang.”<ref>{{Cite book|language=ja|author={{ill|Sadayoshi Sekino|ja|関野貞|12=draft}}|date=1914|title=The Ruins of the Lelang-Daebang Period in Korea|series=Anthropological Magazine 29 (10)|publisher={{ill|Japanese Society of Anthropology|ja|日本人類学会|12=draft}}|page=379}}</ref>

Scholar {{ill|Kazuhiko Itō|ja|伊藤一彦|12=draft}} has pointed out that “in Lelang Commandery not only officials from {{ill|China|ja|中国|12=draft}} but also many {{ill|merchants|ja|Merchant|12=draft}} and {{ill|farmers|ja|農民|12=draft}} migrated, bringing the culture of the Central Plains to Korea. Numerous ruins and artifacts have been excavated from Pyongyang, the capital.”<ref>{{Cite book|language=ja|author={{ill|Kazuhiko Itō|ja|伊藤一彦|12=draft}}|date=2020-03-20|title=History of China–Korea Relations Prior to the 7th Century|series=Economic Studies 87 (3･4)|publisher={{ill|Hosei University Faculty of Economics|ja|法政大学経済学部学会|12=draft}}|page=168}}</ref>

{{ill|Ryū Konishi|ja|今西龍|12=draft}} has remarked, “This once independent petty ruler, {{ill|Zhang Tong|ja|張統 (前燕)|lt=Zhang Tong|lt_ja=張統|12=draft}}, eventually led over a thousand households to join {{ill|Murong Chui|ja|慕容廆|12=draft}} in the fourth month of the first year of the {{ill|Jianxing|ja|建興 (晋)|lt=Jianxing|lt_ja=建興|12=draft}} era ({{ill|313 AD|ja|313rd year|12=draft}}). From that time onward, the Datong River basin was undoubtedly incorporated into the territory of {{ill|Goguryeo|ja|高句麗|12=draft}}, which, having placed particular emphasis on Pyongyang during its earlier period, ultimately transferred its capital to Pyongyang in the 15th year of the reign of {{ill|King Jangsu|ja|長寿王|12=draft}} after more than a century. At that time, Goguryeo, already enriched by the excellent {{ill|Chinese civilization|ja|中国文明|lt=Sinic culture|lt_ja=支那文化|12=draft}}, further imported Chinese culture into the Datong River basin and prospered for over three hundred years until it was finally overthrown in the first year of {{ill|Zongzhang|ja|総章|12=draft}} by {{ill|Emperor Gaozong of Tang|ja|高宗 (唐)|lt=Gaozong of Tang|lt_ja=唐の高宗|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Tang dynasty|ja|唐|12=draft}}. Although the Tang government attempted to directly administer the area by establishing the {{ill|Andong Protectorate|ja|安東都護府|12=draft}}, difficulties forced them to relocate the protectorate to the {{ill|Liaodong Peninsula|ja|遼東半島|lt=Liaodong|lt_ja=遼東|12=draft}} shortly thereafter.”<ref>{{Cite book|language=ja|author={{ill|Ryū Konishi|ja|今西龍|12=draft}}|date=1912-01|title=The Relationship Between the Tombs South of the Datong River and the Lelang Kings|series=Journal of Oriental Studies 2 (1)|publisher={{ill|Toyo Bunko|ja|東洋文庫|12=draft}}|page=99}}</ref>

== Revisionism ==
The Lelang tomb mounds are widely distributed in the {{ill|Pyongyang Area|ja|平壌直轄市|lt=Pyongyang Area|lt_ja=平壌地域|12=draft}} – the core area of the colony established by the Han dynasty on the {{ill|Korean Peninsula|ja|朝鮮半島|12=draft}}, namely in the area of the former {{ill|Lelang Commandery|ja|楽浪郡|12=draft}}, as well as in the {{ill|Hwangae Area|ja|黄海南道|lt=Hwangae Area|lt_ja=黄海道地域|12=draft}} where the later-severed {{ill|Daebang Commandery|ja|帯方郡|12=draft}} was located. In other words, they are found in locations such as Lelang-dong in the Lelang area, Dotun-dong Sukwang-ri, Namsa-ri, Jeongbaek-dong, and in Namseok-ri within {{ill|Sunchon City|ja|順川市|12=draft}}. This discovery emphasizes that Lelang Commandery dominated the area around Pyongyang and underscores the enormous influence the Han dynasty exerted on the development of Korea.<ref name="Pai127">{{Cite book|language=ja|title=Constructing “Korean” Origins: A Critical Review of Archaeology, Historiography, and Racial Myth in Korean State Formation Theories|first=Hyung Il|last=Pai|publisher=Harvard University Asia Center|year=2000|pages=127-129}}</ref> Scholars from {{ill|North Korea|ja|朝鮮民主主義人民共和国|lt=North Korea|lt_ja=北朝鮮|12=draft}} reinterpret these tombs—originally treated as Han dynasty tombs—as part of the Goguryeo burial system.<ref name="Pai127"/> Due to artifacts bearing undeniable similarities to Chinese Han tombs, North Korean scholars contend that the tomb occupants were either Goguryeo people or even forgeries, and they argue that “the tombs’ distinctly Korean characteristics should never be dismissed as evidence to the contrary.”<ref>{{Cite journal|language=ja|title=An Outline History of Korean Historiography|first=Yŏng-ho|last=Ch'oe|journal=Korean Studies|volume=4|year=1980|page=509|publisher=University of Hawaiʻi Press|doi=10.1353/ks.1980.0003}}</ref> According to these scholars, the interpretation of the tombs as Han dynasty tombs was a fabrication concocted by sinocentric ideologues and {{ill|Japanese imperialism|ja|日本帝国主義|lt=Japanese imperialism|lt_ja=日本帝国主義者|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|language=ja|title=An Outline History of Korean Historiography|first=Yŏng-ho|last=Ch'oe|journal=Korean Studies|volume=4|year=1980|pages=23-25|publisher=University of Hawaiʻi Press|doi=10.1353/ks.1980.0003}}</ref>

