[[sn:Lelang tomb clusters]] [[ko:낙랑 고분]] [[ja:楽浪古墳群]]

'''Lelang Tomb Mound Cluster''' (楽浪古墳群) is a cluster of ancient tomb mounds excavated from the southern to eastern areas of the site of the administrative center of {{ill|Lelang Commandery|ja|楽浪郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, a colony established on the {{ill|Korean Peninsula|ja|朝鮮半島|12=draft|12=draft}} by the {{ill|Han dynasty|ja|漢|lt=Han dynasty|lt_ja=漢王朝|12=draft|12=draft}}’s {{ill|Emperor Wu of Han|ja|武帝 (漢)|lt=Emperor Wu of Han|lt_ja=武帝|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|108 BC|ja|紀元前108th year|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="Lelang Tomb Mound Cluster">{{Kotobank|楽浪古墳群|{{ill|Encyclopedia of the World|ja|世界大百科事典|12=draft|12=draft}}}}</ref> According to the prevailing academic theory, the location of {{ill|Lelang Commandery|ja|楽浪郡|12=draft|12=draft}} corresponds to present-day {{ill|Pyongyang|ja|平壌直轄市|lt=Pyongyang City|lt_ja=平壌市|12=draft|12=draft}} and its surroundings.<ref>{{Cite news|author=|date=2015-12-14|title=“Misinterpretation of the Creation Date of Historical Materials” – A professor at Hanbock University refutes the theory that “the Great Wall of Myriad Li reaches Pyongyang”|publisher=|newspaper={{ill|Dong-A Ilbo|ja|東亜日報|12=draft|12=draft}}|url=https://www.donga.com/jp/article/all/20151214/430197/1|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20221027105756/https://www.donga.com/jp/article/all/20151214/430197/1|archivedate=2022-10-27}}</ref> In the area around {{ill|Pyongyang|ja|平壌直轄市|lt=Pyongyang City|lt_ja=平壌市|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Lelang area|ja|楽浪区域|12=draft|12=draft}}, particularly near Jeongbaek-dong, over a thousand tomb mounds are found clustered together.<ref name="Lelang Tomb Mound Cluster"/>
== Overview == The tomb mounds of the Lelang cluster underwent a transition from the {{ill|Mokgak Tomb|ja|木槨墳|12=draft|12=draft}} style to the {{ill|Yochiku Tomb|ja|塼築墳|12=draft|12=draft}} style around the turn from the {{ill|1st century|ja|1世紀|12=draft|12=draft}} to the {{ill|2nd century|ja|2世紀|12=draft|12=draft}}. Since the {{ill|Yochiku Tomb|ja|塼築墳|12=draft|12=draft}} style in the Lelang tomb mounds was generally constructed from around the {{ill|2nd century|ja|2世紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, they are believed to be associated with the ruling class of both {{ill|Lelang Commandery|ja|楽浪郡|lt=Lelang|lt_ja=楽浪|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Daebang Commandery|ja|帯方郡|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="이성제"/> Among these, there are some Yochiku Tombs from which epitaphs bearing chronological inscriptions have been unearthed that indicate construction after {{ill|313 AD|ja|313rd year|12=draft|12=draft}}, when {{ill|Goguryeo|ja|高句麗|12=draft|12=draft}} came to dominate {{ill|Lelang Commandery|ja|楽浪郡|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Daebang Commandery|ja|帯方郡|12=draft|12=draft}}. For instance, a chronological inscription on a Yochiku Tomb unearthed in {{ill|South Hwanghae Province|ja|黄海南道|12=draft|12=draft}}’s {{ill|Sinchon County|ja|信川郡|12=draft|12=draft}} reads “Second day, second month, 8th year of Yonghe,” indicating construction in {{ill|404 AD|ja|404th year|12=draft|12=draft}} when Goguryeo was using the era name {{ill|Yongle (Goguryeo)|ja|永楽 (高句麗)|lt=Yongle (Goguryeo)|lt_ja=永楽|12=draft|12=draft}}, yet the epitaph employs the era name of the {{ill|Eastern Jin|ja|東晋|12=draft|12=draft}}, suggesting that the inhabitants of Lelang and Daebang Commandery maintained an identity affiliated not with Goguryeo but with {{ill|China|ja|中国|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="이성제">{{Cite news|author=이성제|date=|title=Immigrants of the period of contention between the Northern and Southern dynasties in the Six States and their relation to Goguryeo and Baekje|publisher={{ill|National History Compilation Committee|ja|国史編纂委員会|12=draft|12=draft}}|newspaper=|url=http://contents.nahf.or.kr/id/NAHF.edeah.d_0002_0010_0040|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123050319/http://contents.nahf.or.kr/id/NAHF.edeah.d_0002_0010_0040|archivedate=2022-11-23}}</ref>
