manderies until both had vanished around AD 313. In Lelang and Daebang, officials from {{ill|China|ja|支那|12=draft|12=draft}} were stationed, and many {{ill|Han people|ja|漢民族|12=draft|12=draft}} settled there, importing Han {{ill|culture|ja|文化|1=Bunka|2=ja|3=文化 (元号)|4=de|5=Bunka (Ära)|6=ko|7=분카|12=draft|12=draft}}; recent investigations have uncovered various relics in and around Pyongyang.”<ref>{{Cite book|language=ja|author={{ill|Sadayoshi Sekino|ja|関野貞|12=draft|12=draft}}|date=1914|title=The Ruins of the Lelang-Daebang Period in Korea|series=Anthropological Magazine 29 (10)|publisher={{ill|Japanese Society of Anthropology|ja|日本人類学会|12=draft|12=draft}}|page=379}}</ref>
Scholar {{ill|Kazuhiko Itō|ja|伊藤一彦|12=draft|12=draft}} has pointed out that “in Lelang Commandery not only officials from {{ill|China|ja|中国|12=draft|12=draft}} but also many {{ill|merchants|ja|Merchant|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|farmers|ja|農民|12=draft|12=draft}} migrated, bringing the culture of the Central Plains to Korea. Numerous ruins and artifacts have been excavated from Pyongyang, the capital.”<ref>{{Cite book|language=ja|author={{ill|Kazuhiko Itō|ja|伊藤一彦|12=draft|12=draft}}|date=2020-03-20|title=History of China–Korea Relations Prior to the 7th Century|series=Economic Studies 87 (3･4)|publisher={{ill|Hosei University Faculty of Economics|ja|法政大学経済学部学会|12=draft|12=draft}}|page=168}}</ref>
