Scholar {{ill|Kazuhiko Itō|ja|伊藤一彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kazuhiko Itō|qq=}} has pointed out that “in Lelang Commandery not only officials from {{ill|China|ja|中国|1=China (region)|2=ja|3=中国|lt=China|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/China|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} but also many {{ill|merchants|ja|Merchant|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/merchants|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and [[:en:Peasant|farmers]] migrated, bringing the culture of the Central Plains to Korea. Numerous ruins and artifacts have been excavated from Pyongyang, the capital.”<ref>{{Cite book|language=ja|author={{ill|Kazuhiko Itō|ja|伊藤一彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kazuhiko Itō|qq=}}|date=2020-03-20|title=History of China–Korea Relations Prior to the 7th Century|series=Economic Studies 87 (3･4)|publisher={{ill|Hosei University Faculty of Economics|ja|法政大学経済学部学会|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hosei University Faculty of Economics|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}|page=168}}</ref>
{{ill|Ryū Konishi|ja|今西龍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ryū Konishi|qq=}} has remarked, “This once independent petty ruler, {{ill|Zhang Tong|ja|張統 (前燕)|lt=Zhang Tong|lt_ja=張統|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zhang Tong|qq=}}, eventually led over a thousand households to join [[:en:Murong Hui|Murong Chui]] in the fourth month of the first year of the {{ill|Jianxing|ja|建興 (晋)|lt=Jianxing|lt_ja=建興|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jianxing|qq=}} era ([[:en:313|313 AD]]). From that time onward, the Datong River basin was undoubtedly incorporated into the territory of [[:en:Goguryeo|Goguryeo]], which, having placed particular emphasis on Pyongyang during its earlier period, ultimately transferred its capital to Pyongyang in the 15th year of the reign of [[:en:Jangsu of Goguryeo|King Jangsu]] after more than a century. At that time, Goguryeo, already enriched by the excellent {{ill|Chinese civilization|ja|中国文明|lt=Sinic culture|lt_ja=支那文化|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinese civilization|qq=}}, further imported Chinese culture into the Datong River basin and prospered for over three hundred years until it was finally overthrown in the first year of {{ill|Zongzhang|ja|総章|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zongzhang|qq=}} by [[:en:Emperor Gaozong of Tang|Gaozong of Tang]] of the [[:en:Tang dynasty|Tang dynasty]]. Although the Tang government attempted to directly administer the area by establishing the [[:en:Protectorate General to Pacify the East|Andong Protectorate]], difficulties forced them to relocate the protectorate to the [[:en:Liaodong Peninsula|Liaodong]] shortly thereafter.”<ref>{{Cite book|language=ja|author={{ill|Ryū Konishi|ja|今西龍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ryū Konishi|qq=}}|date=1912-01|title=The Relationship Between the Tombs South of the Datong River and the Lelang Kings|series=Journal of Oriental Studies 2 (1)|publisher=[[:en:Tōyō Bunko|Toyo Bunko]]|page=99}}</ref>
== Revisionism == The Lelang tomb mounds are widely distributed in the {{ill|Pyongyang Area|ja|平壌直轄市|lt=Pyongyang Area|lt_ja=平壌地域|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Pyongyang Area|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 平壌市}} – the core area of the colony established by the Han dynasty on the {{ill|Korean Peninsula|ja|朝鮮半島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Korean Peninsula|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, namely in the area of the former [[:en:Lelang Commandery|Lelang Commandery]], as well as in the [[:en:South Hwanghae Province|Hwangae Area]] where the later-severed [[:en:Daifang Commandery|Daebang Commandery]] was located. In other words, they are found in locations such as Lelang-dong in the Lelang area, Dotun-dong Sukwang-ri, Namsa-ri, Jeongbaek-dong, and in Namseok-ri within [[:en:Sunchon|Sunchon City]]. This discovery emphasizes that Lelang Commandery dominated the area around Pyongyang and underscores the enormous influence the Han dynasty exerted on the development of Korea.<ref name="Pai127">{{Cite book|language=ja|title=Constructing “Korean” Origins: A Critical Review of Archaeology, Historiography, and Racial Myth in Korean State Formation Theories|first=Hyung Il|last=Pai|publisher=Harvard University Asia Center|year=2000|pages=127-129}}</ref> Scholars from [[:en:North Korea|North Korea]] reinterpret these tombs—originally treated as Han dynasty tombs—as part of the Goguryeo burial system.<ref name="Pai127"/> Due to artifacts bearing undeniable similarities to Chinese Han tombs, North Korean scholars contend that the tomb occupants were either Goguryeo people or even forgeries, and they argue that “the tombs’ distinctly Korean characteristics should never be dismissed as evidence to the contrary.”<ref>{{Cite journal|language=ja|title=An Outline History of Korean Historiography|first=Yŏng-ho|last=Ch'oe|journal=Korean Studies|volume=4|year=1980|page=509|publisher=University of Hawaiʻi Press|doi=10.1353/ks.1980.0003}}</ref> According to these scholars, the interpretation of the tombs as Han dynasty tombs was a fabrication concocted by sinocentric ideologues and [[:en:Japanese colonial empire|Japanese imperialism]].<ref>{{Cite journal|language=ja|title=An Outline History of Korean Historiography|first=Yŏng-ho|last=Ch'oe|journal=Korean Studies|volume=4|year=1980|pages=23-25|publisher=University of Hawaiʻi Press|doi=10.1353/ks.1980.0003}}</ref>
